{{Short description|Microscopic finding in the sputum of asthmatics}}
[[File:Curshman's_Spiral.jpg|thumb|250px|Curschmann's spiral]]
'''Curschmann's spirals''' are a microscopic finding in the [[sputum]] of asthmatics. They are spiral-shaped mucus plugs from subepithelial mucous gland ducts of bronchi. They may occur in several different lung diseases<ref name="pmid9812228">{{cite journal |vauthors=Cenci M, Giovagnoli MR, Alderisio M, Vecchione A |title=Curschmann's spirals in sputum of subjects exposed daily to urban environmental pollution |journal=Diagn. Cytopathol. |volume=19 |issue=5 |pages=349–51 |date=November 1998 |pmid=9812228|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-0339(199811)19:5<349::AID-DC7>3.0.CO;2-7|s2cid=5638354 }}</ref> and may refer to parts of the [[desquamation|desquamated]] [[epithelium]] seen in lavages from asthmatic patients.<ref name="urlCurschmanns spiral in sputum from asthma patient">{{cite web |url=http://www.som.tulane.edu/classware/pathology/medical_pathology/New_for_98/Lung_Review/Lung-29.html |title=Curschmann's spiral in sputum from asthma patient |access-date=2008-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090429164750/http://www.som.tulane.edu/classware/pathology/medical_pathology/New_for_98/Lung_Review/Lung-29.html |archive-date=2009-04-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> These microscopic casts are named after German physician [[Heinrich Curschmann]] (1846-1910). They are often seen in association with [[creola bodies]] and [[Charcot-Leyden crystals]]. They are elongated microscopic mucous casts from small bronchi and are often found in sputum samples from patients with bronchial asthma. They can be stretched out to a length of around 2&nbsp;cm and can sometimes be longer. They have a central core that may be ensheathed in cell debris and mucus.<ref>Academic Dictionaries; Academic 2014</ref>

